results.notes:
Habitat: bottomland deciduous woods including oaks, sourwood, and rhododendron
Cap: diameter 77 mm, broadly convex with a low umbo. Smooth with a tacky surface. Dark grayish brown over the umbo, paler and radially streaked to the periphery. Stains brown where injured. No marginal striations
Gills: crowded, free, pinkish cream, short gills numerous, attenuate, of varying lengths. Gill depth to 4 mm at the thickest point, roughly midway to the margin. Brown staining absent to minimal. Gill edges rough—tufted?
Stipe: 150 mm long x 15 mm thick, equal, fibrillose, creamy with some brown stains on fibrils and around injuries. Basal bulb soft, 27 × 18 mm, no vertical cracks. Flesh cream-colored and fibrous, hollowing in the lower section. Free limb of the thick, saccate volva to 15 mm long
Partial veil: membranous, apical, thin, white. The upper surface is radially lined; lower surface roughened. Mostly attached to the stipe, but rags also adherent to the cap margin
Odor: none

results.notes:
On disintegrating sandstone boulder along an ephemeral drainage.

Thallus a thick brown crust composed of small imbricate squamules. On shady sides the color is yellow-brown, in full sun dark brown. Squamules appear to have whitish lower cortex. Spot tests negative. Thick epinecral layer present. Prothallus absent. Apothecia irregularly common, adnate, plane to concave, with a thick thalline margin, often flexuous, disk red-brown to nearly black, epruinose, roughened, unchanging when wet. Epihymenium red-brown, unchanging in K, POL-. Amphithecium with a pocket of algae and an epinecral layer over the cortex, POL+. Hymenium hyaline. Paraphyses conglutinated. Hymenial gel K/I+Blue. Asci tholus amyloid. Pycnidia common, immersed. Conidia filiform, curved, about 20×1µm.

Spores 0-1 septate, hyaline, narrowly ellipsoid, somewhat curved, ends often tapering. Average size 19.9×4.4µm (n=4).

I chose to include this in the NAMP project because there is a considerable lack of closure regarding the North American taxon formerly known as Suillus granulatus. It is clear that the species name “granulatus” does not apply to any NA species of Suillus. However, there appears to be confusion regarding an acceptable name for the NA “granulatus”. Recently, the species name “weaverae” has been proposed. But, there is reason to believe that the entity originally assigned the species name “weaverae” is not the same taxon as what had been called “granulatus” in NA. Moreover, somewhat variable morphology suggests there may be more than one species represented by the NA “granulatus”.

I have proposed as an alternative ID “Suillus weaverae”, because this name has been proposed for this (or for a similar) taxon.

results.notes:
A single basidiome growing in grass at the base of a planted Betula papyrifera that’s been dying for the last few years. There are a few yellow birches planted across a trail a few yards away, but other than these there are no other mycorrhizal tree hosts in the immediate vicinity, save maybe an ash; other trees nearby are sweet gums and maples, with a few white pines ~40 yards away. I’ve never seen this species in this spot, though A. solaniolens was found a few years ago under the yellow birches across the trail.
The cap is oval-shaped, 4.5-4.8 cm wide; the marginal striations are up to 7 mm long; the short gills are plentiful, of various lengths, and are trunctate to sub-truncate; the stipe is 5.5 cm long and ~1 cm wide at the narrowest point; the bulb is 1.6 cm wide. The rest of the morphology can be inferred from the pix. Looks like a read-ringer for A. crenulata, except the spores are globose to subglobose (as visualized at x400 with no mounting medium), and the fruiting is unusually early for it; as a matter of fact, this is my first amanita of the season found under deciduous trees.

Fruit body immature; I scoped some gill material but found no spores. Also, left out a piece of cap for a print, but no print developed.

Cap surface smooth with two thick patches of universal veil. Universal veil otherwise deposited along the stipe surface as fragile white plates. KOH on cap surface negative (applied 20 hours after collection; bleached out the graying stain).
